{"/service/ndnp/arhi/batch_arhi_dioptase_ver02/data/sn92050145/00516990351/1930081501/0682.xml":{"full_text":"HEADS OF BIG TEN INDUSTRIES AGAINST WAGE CUTS\nNew York City.\u2014Ten big industrial leaders declared\nagainst wage cuts in an article written by Roy Dickinson,\nassisant editor and member of the Harding Unemploy\nment Conference.\nExtracts from the statements of the ten employers\nfollow:\nGEORGE F. JOHNSON, president, Endicott Johnson Cor\nporation\u2014Reducing income of labor la not a remedy for business\ndepression; it is a direct and contributing cause.\nR. 8. SSAINWALD, president Paraffine Companies, Inc.\u2014\nThe Paraffine Companies, Inc., believes such reduction can and\nshould be avoided.\nC. R. PALMER, president, Cluett, Peabody Co.\u2014In my\nopinion, a general reduction of wages and salaries at this time is\nentirely unwarranted.\nW. A. SHEAFFER, president, W. A. Sheaffer Pen Company\u2014\nBelieve it would be serious mistake to reduce wages.\nA. K. ERSK1NE. president Studebaker Company\u2014Have not\neven considered reducing wages or salaries.\nA. C. LOKING, president, Pillsbury Flour Mills Company\u2014\nThe new spirit in industry\u2019 starts a virtuous, and not a vicious,\ncircle in motion.\nHERBERT V. KOHLER, executive vice president, Kohler\nCompany- Kohler Company is maintaining its organization and its\nwage scale.\nHOWARD COOXLEY, president, Walworth Company\u2014-The\nWalworth Company has no thought of reducing salaries or wages.\nHAROLD C. KEITH, president. George E. Keith Company\u2014\nWhile our company has made no reduction and contemplates\nnone yet conditions might force such changes at a later time.\nARTHUR ROEDEK, president, Colorado Fuel and Iron Com\npany\u2014You probably remember Bob Ingersoll\u2019s reply when asked\nhow he would improve the world. He said he would make\nhealth uangerous instead of disease.\n\u201cTen years ago.\u201d Dickinson writes, summing up the\nreplies in Printers\u2019 Ink. \"when I was a member of Presi\ndent Harding\u2019s Unemployment Conference run by Her\nbert Hoover. I wrote a miuority report against wage\ncuts. 1 could get only one of the fifty members to sign\nit\u2014the late Samuel Gompcrs. Then it was almost an\naxiom that wage cuts would bring back normal times.\n\"Today a new point of view prevails- Maintaining\npurchasing power at the source is the most important\njob in the country today, for wages buy more shoes and\nautomobiles than dividends.\u2019\u2019\nBringing You Official Labor News That\nYon Can Get Only Through Your\nLabor Paper.\nUnion Labor Bulletin\n__ Arkansas' Official Labor Publication.\nReaching the Best-Paid Class of\nPeople as a Whole in the State.\nV0L.XXX1I. No. 33.\n\nLITTLE ROCK, ARKANSAS, Al'GLST 13, 1930\nFIVE CENTS\nROSE BUD DIVISION NO. 283\nTO BE HOST TO GRAND OFFICER\nOctober 7th Is Date Set to Entertain Mrs. Emma Coleman,\nDeputy Grand President of Auxiliary to Order\nof Railway Conductors.\nBy Mr*. Andie Pearce. Pre*.\nBone Bad Auxiliary No. 283 to\ntile Order of Railway Conductors,\nmet in regular session Tuesday,\nAugust 8, In their lodge room lo\ncated in-the W. 0. W. Hall, this\ncity.\nHie meeting was called to order\nprbmptly by the president and an\nunutually good attendance was\npresent\nlike all other auxiliaries, the\nAuxiliary to the Railway Conduc\ntors decided to have a float in the\nparade on Labor Day and plans\nwere consummated at this meeting\nregarding the decoration\nIt was decided to hold an all-day\nmeeting at the home of Mrs. J. W.\nWeed, 821 Arkansas avenue, North\nV Arthur Brisbane\nHard on Stock Gamblers\nA New Great Flyer\n346,095,925 in 2030\nGaa Merchants, Attention\nStock gambling in dull, uncertain\ntimes is most annoying to gamb\nlers. They never can be quite sure.\nWall Street heard of the drought,\nand wise bulls said: \u201cThat will kill\n*rain crops, and with less wheat\n.and com, prices will go up. The\ntow price of wheat has held stocks\ndown. Let us buy stocks and they\nwill go up with wheat.\u2019'\nr They bought stocks and they did\nnot go up when wheat and com\nwent up.\nThe bears said: \u201cThis is our op\nportunity. We sympathize with the\nBuffering public, especially the\nfarmer. When drought kills crops,\nthat will injure all the people, and\nitocks will go down. This is Lie\nlime to sell them.\u201d\nThey sold them and stocks did\nnot go doom enough to make it\nworth while.\nStock gambling is very wearing\nexcept for bulls in good times, and\nfor bears in panics. Then it is \u201clike\ntaking candy from a sick child\u201d.\nCaptain Hawks, who stands out\nbow as the greatest American fly*\ner, Hit New York at six o\u2019clock in\n,Kj> morning, eastern daylight\ntinw, landed in Los Angeles at 50\nminutes past 4:00 p. m., Pacific\nstandard time, keeping an appoint\nment to play golf, at the edge of\nthe Tacific, after leaving that\nmorning the edge of the Atlantic.\nHis flying time, all in broad day\nlight, was less than fifteen hours,\nsad be made five stops for gaso\nline. That will not be necessary in\nfuture days, with better machines\nand- better fuel.\nIa \u201cContinental United \u2019States\"\ndll population ia 122,720,472. Uncle\n5auf says so. This does not include\nPorto Rico, the Philippines or Ha\nwaii,\nIs\u2018ten years population has in\n18.1 per cent If that in\nitial. continues, our population\ni Wars hence, in 2030, will be\nib,0|6,925.\nI Labor union experts reading that\n.(Continued on Page 2)\nLittle Rock, on August 19, where\nflowers will be made to decorate\nthe float.\nThe first Tuesday in October\nthis auxiliary will be honored with\nthe presence of Mrs. Emma Cole\nman, Grand Deputy President of\nthe Auxiliary to the Order of Rail\nway Conductors. An all-day meet\ning will be held at that date and a\nluncheon will be served in the hall.\nMrs. Grace Wheeling, Grand\nPresident, of Oklahoma City, Okla*,\nhas also been invited and has tent\natively accepted the invitation, but\nit is not definite that she will be\nhere like it is with the Deputy\nGrand President, but since she or\nganized this division, No. 283, it is\nhoped that nothing prevents her\nattending.\nWHEAT OUTPUT\nLIMIT DIFFICULT\nTO EFFECT\nWashington. The weakness of\nthe Federal Farm Board\u2019s policy of\na 25 per cent reduction of wheat\nacreage to enable the wheat grow\ners to boost wheat prices to a\nprofitable figure is apparently the\nlack of an adequate system of com\npulsion to insure the acreage reduc\ntion which the board claims is ne\ncessary.\nThe board\u2019s policy is to restrict\nwheat production to an acreage\nthat will satisfy the demands of the\npeople of the United States. When\nthis limit is reached the board be\nlieves the tariff on wheat will as\nsert itself in the interest of better\nprices.\nIt is apparent to those who study\nfarm prices that a curtailment of\n10 per cent in wheat acreage, nor\n15 per cent, nor 20 per cent, will\nbe effective, and voluntary reduc\ntion, which depends on the united\naction of thousands of grain grow\ners, does not seem to be dependa\nble. Last winter the board asked\nthe cotton growers voluntarily to\nreduce their acreage 10 per cent.\nThe reply was a reduction of but\n2.7 per cent.\nMoreover, the board is now con\nfronted with the problem of estab\nlishing a policy for the profitable\nuse of the one-quarter of the wheat\nfarmers\u2019 land which the acreage\ncurtailment means that the wheat\ni farmers must leave one-quarter of\ntheir plant idle writh overhead run\nning on all the time.\nINTELLECTUALS URGE\nFREE SPEECH FOR ALL\nAtlanta, Ga.\u2014Free speech and\nthe right of free assemblage for\neverybody, including Communists,\nwas demanded in a statement is\nsued by 62 Atlanta ministers, pro\nfessional men, and prominent wom\nen and college professors.\nThe demand was brought forth\nby the recent arrest and imprison\nment here of six alleged Commun\nists on the charge of inciting to in\nsurrection by the distribution oi\ncirculars advocating Communism,\nThe signers declare they do not en\ndorse the principles of Communism'\nbut insist that the \"Communists\nshould be protected in their consti\ntutional rights of free speech and\nfree assemblage.\nALONG BY-PATHS\nOF THE\nWEEK\u2019S NEWS\nBy Stanley Andrews\nOpinion* \u00abjcpr*u\u00abd in thl* column *r*\nibe penonni opinion* of Mr. Andrew* and\nare not necessarily the policy of the Labor\nBulletin.\u2014The Editor.\nArkansas has just experienced a\nDemocratic primary and as this is\nwritten majorities have been defi\nnitely established in most of the\nmajor races.\nIn the state race the principal\nstate offices, lieutenant governor,\nsecretary of state, land commis\nsioner, treasurer, and other minor\noffices found candidates friendly to\nthe present administration in the\nlead. In the county races largely\nlocal issues dominated and had lit\ntle bearing on the state race.\nThe Senate race turned out about\nas anyone who had carefully sur\nveyed the situation expected.\nWhile Senator Robinson has hie\nenemies Arkansas recognizes his\nability and leadership and w-ants to\nkeep him there.\nSay this for Mr. Campbell his\nrace was above board and persis\ntent but it takes a more stirring\npersonality and a stronger attack\nto turn folks from the record and\nthe following that Senator Robin\nson has.\nExpressed purely a% a personal\nopinion we regard the race for\ngovernor as more or less of an\nelimination of figures that have\nbeen in state politics for many\nyears seeking one office or an\nother.\nHay\u2019s failure to win this time\nprobably eliminates him for con\nsideration for a number of years.\nWith him goes Cazort, Terral, Steel\nHays, and another group that was\nmore or less in power during the\nTerral administration. Sheffield\nfailed to show enough strength to\nI give him a boom two years from\nj now. Tamell of course is merely\n{elected for another two years.\nOut of the present state officials j\nwill come some booms for organiza-'\ntion support but if the truth must!\nhe said there are no men in the j\nlimelight who would run for gover\nnor that has the ability. Likel>\nthen two years from now will se'\na mad scramble for nominations\nI and the likelihood of an outside\nI man coming in. Such would be a\ngood and healthy sign.\nIf one were to analyze public\nsentiment and try to determine the\nreason for the heavy Parnell vote\none would first have to admit that\nthe organization back of Parnell\nwas 100 per cent effective. On top\nof that Parnell has a definite con\nstructive program and whether all\nagree that it was being carried out\nfaithfully or not matters little\u2014at\nleast definite things have been ac\ncomplished.\nThis state is sold on roads at\nany cost and the rural school pro\ngram now being carried out is one\nof the ftest in the South and is at-1\ntrading national attention. j\nWhat the next two years will i\nbring and how faithfully the pro-!\ngra:s outlined will be carried out\ndepends largely upon how alert we\nare as citizens and how much in\nterested we are in our own prob\nlems.\nAt this is written Mr. Hoover\nconferring with governors from the\n(Continued on Page 4)\nLIBBY ROLL LODGE, AUXILIARY TO R. R.\nTRAINMEN, HOLDS PEPPY MEETING\nThe Auxiliary to the Brother\nhood of Railroad Trainmen, better\nknown as Libby Roll Lodge No. 489\nmet in regular session Thursday,\nAugust 7, in the A. O. U. W. build\ning, and in spite of the hot weather,\nand many being away on their va\ncation, a good attendance was pres\nent.\nThe meeting was called to order\npromptly by the president, Mrs.\nMayme Oholendt, and a peppy\nmeeting was held.\nSeveral important measures\nwere acted upon, but one of the\nforemost measures discussed, was\nUNORGANIZED\nWORKERS HAVE\nPOVERTY WAGES\nBaltimore, Md.\u2014Edward F. Mc\nGrady, an organizer for the Amer\nican Federation of Labor, assisted\nthe International Ladies' Garment\nWorkers\u2019 Union in its strike here\nagainst sweatshops, low wages and\nmiserable working conditions. In a\nnumber of speeches McGrady\nclaimed that \u201cone-quarter of the\nworking men and women of Balti\nmore are living in poverty and that\ntheir wages do not supply the ne\nj cessary food, clothing and other\nnecessities for a decent life.\u201d He\nalso declared that \u201cthere is another\nj quarter of the workers whose in\ncomes allow them\u2019 the bare necessi\nties but usually not enough of the\nproper nourishment to keep them\nin good health.\u201d Mr. McGrady\npointed out that these two groups\nare largely unorganized wofVers.\nThe statements about poverty\nand near poverty by the A. F. of\nL. organizer were challenged, but\nrecent official figures give good\nI support to their correctness.\nThe Peoples\u2019 Court declares that\n\u201cthe usual decrease in poverty\ncases generally expected in sum\nmer did not materialize this year.\u201d\nChief Constable Doyle submitted\nj figures showing that 11,735 poor\ni persons wfere evicted from the\nhomes during the first six months\nof 1930, compared with 9.140 evic\ntions during the first six moriths\nof 1929.\nRent cases which formerly num\nbered about 35 a day have now\njumped to 125 per day.\nMr. McGrady maintained that\nthese figures would continue to\ngrow and that the only salvation\nfor the Baltimore workers is or\nganization. The strike cf the La\ndies\u2019 Garment Worker was success\nful. They obtained the union shop,\nshorter working hours and In\ncreased wages.\n19,445 R. R. WORKERS\nKILLED AND INJURED\nDetroit, Mich. Three hundred\nand ninety-four maintenance-of\nway employes on railroads with op\nerating revenues of $1,000,000 or\nmore per year were killed in 1928\nand 19,051 were Injured, declares\nthe Brotherhood of Maintenance\nof-Way Employes. The figures are\ncompiled from data collected by the\nUnited States Interstate Commerce\nCommission. The death and injury\nrates are higher among these em\nployes than for any other group of\nrailroad workers except train and\nengine crews, and considerably\nhigher than for all railroad em\nployes combined.\nthe part this auxiliary want ini to\ntake in the Statewide Labor Day\nparade. This subject was discussed\nat length and a special meeting\nwas called at the home of the\npresident, Mrs. Oholcndt, 1611 Pop\nlar street, North Little Hock, to\ndiscuss this matter more fully.\nAnother matter of interest was\nthat this lodge had a new candidate\nfor initiation.\nThe lodge adjourned to meet\nagain at the regular meeting date\nin the future, besides the special\nmeeting to be at the home of the\npresident.\nWAGE CUTS SUICIDAL\nFOR BUSINESS REVIVAL\nNew York.\u2014The suggestion of\nthe Wall .Street Journal and similar\nreactionary employer agencies that\nemployers should use the drastic\nreduction in prices which has taken\nplace this year as a reason for at\ntempting to enforce wage reduc\ntions \u201chas evoked no sympathetic\nresponse from the country\u2019s indus\ntrial leaders,\u201d declares the New\nYork World in an editorial which\nuses the recent declaration of the\nexecutives of a number of large\nmanufacturing companies against\nwage reductions to confirm this\nview. \u201cThe concensus among them\nwas that such a policy, instead of\nj relieving depression, would only\ntend to accentuate it,\u2019 the World\nsays.\nWhile admitting that certain em.\nplovers have already made \u201cspo\nradic wage reductions\u201d and ex\npressing the fear that the \u201cspo\nradic\u201d wage reducers may increase,\nthe World insists that \u201cthe determ\nination of representative captains\nof industry to maintain wage scales\nis one of the best assurances of a\nj business revival on a sound basis\nj as soo.i as demand and supply are\nibrought into better alignment. And:\none of the surest ways of post- j\nponing the return to normal would\nhe a conserted effort of employers j\nto \u2018take it out on labor\u2019.\u201d\nRUSSIAN COMMUNISM\nMENACE TO AMERICA\nBoston, Mass.\u2014\u201cThe attempt of\ncommunistic Russia to infiltrate\nthe free governments of the world\nwith its propaganda and doctrine\nhas been an open and brazen at\ntempt to undermine the American\ngovernment,\u201d declares Gov. Frank\nG. Allen of Massachusetts.\n\u201cThe brazen and open manner in\nwhich Russia's dictator has at\ntempted to dominate the field of\nAmerican economics should be suf\nficient to alert all patriotic organ\nizations to the gravity of the sit\nuation,\u201d the governor says. \u201cIt\nshould inspire with a determina\ntion to combat vigorously in every\ncomer of our land the vicious at\ntempt to impose upon America a\nj system of government foreign to\nours, and which has been branded\nas a complete failure.\u201d\nGovernor Allen contends that\nnumerous instances of apparent\neconomic conflict in the United\nStates have not been the \u201cgenuine\ncomplaint of Americans, but the\nmasterly connivance of propagand\nists seeking to spread the seed of\ndiscontent and unrest.\u201d\nMETAL WORKERS UNITE\nNashville, Tenn. Sheet metal\nworkers organized as has elevator\nerectors. This is one result of an\norganizing campaign that is inter\nesting many locals. _\nSUPREME COURT\nKILLED MINIMUM\nWAGE LAWS\nWashington. The reaction ef\nfect on social welfare legislation of\ntlie power arrogated to itself by\nthe United States Supreme Court\nto nullify laws enacted by the Con\ngress of the United States and ap\nproved by the President is stressed\nby the U. S. Women\u2019s Bureau in a\nstatement on the status of mini\nmum wage laws for women.\nOnly eight states now have min\nimum wage laws, and only seven are\nenforcing them. The Colorado law\nis a dead letter because the legis\nlature refuses to make an appro\npriation for its enforcement.\nIn 1922, the District of Columbia\nminimum wage law, making it\nmandatory for employers in the\ncapital of the nation to pay women\nworkers in certain industries at\nleast a living wage, was disap- j\nproved by the majority of the Su\npreme Court as imposing an un\nwarranted burden on low-wage em\nployers, who had the legal and\nmoral fight, according to the ma\njority, to buy the labor power of\nworking women on exactly the\nsame basis ns they bought com\nmodities like potatoes and bread.\nThe majority declared that if the!\neconomic necessities of working\nwomen compelled them to sell their\nlabor power for less than a living\nwage, the low-wage employers were\nneither morally nor legally respon\nsible for that condition, and held\nthat compelling the employers of\nworking women to pay them a\nliving wage was a violation of the\nemployers\u2019 rights set out in the\nConstitution of the United States.\nThe majority of the court therefore\nnullified the minimum wage law\nas unconstitutional.\nThe Women\u2019s Bureau states that\nthe decision of the Supreme Court\nnullifying the District of Columbia\nlaw set a precedent of declaring a\nminimum wage law invalid. Follow\ning the decision some states nulli\nfied similar laws and the Interest\nin their enforcement was lessened\nin other states.\nAccording to the bureau\u2019s state\nment the argument against mini\nmum v'age laws to the effect that\nthey tend to fix maximum wages is\nnot based on fact. The California\nminimum wage law is cited as an\noutHanding example of the ten\ndency of such laws to push wages\nup father than lower them.\nSTATE OLD-AGE\nPENSIONS FORM\nOF PAUPER RELIEF\nAlbany, N. Y. Old age \u201cpen\nsions\u201d in New York state will 1*/.*,\nlimited to needy persons 70 years\nold and over, declared Charles H. I\nJohnson, commissioner of the state i\ndepartment of social welfare. In\nfact, the \u201cpension\u201d is not a pension\nat all, but a system of poor relief.\nTo secure the modest \u201crelief\u201d a\nperson must be 70 years of age,\nunable to support himself either in\nwhole or in part, and have no re\nlation or other person able to sup\nport him and responsible under the\nlaw for his support. Persons living\ncontinuously in institutions are not\neligible for the relief.\nFARM WAGES DROP\nWashington. Farm wage* de\ncreased 2 per cent from April 1 to\nJuly 1, according to the Bureau of\nAgricultural Economics.\nDuring this time, usually, there\nis a seasonal increase of 6 per cent,\nI it A iul\nLADIES\u2019 SOCIETY TO L F. E.\nTRANSACT REGULAR BUSINESS AUG. 12\nBy Ethel Robinson\nAugust 12 was the date for the\nprimary election and in spite of the\nfact that most of the members of\nthe iadies society to the Brother\nhood of Locomotive Firemen and\nEnginemen were at the polls work\ning for their friends, the lodge con\nvened as usual in their regular\nmeeting place, Guenters Hall,\nMarkham anil Cross streets with\nMrs. Dora Strickland in the chair\nas president.\nMrs. C. E. Chastain acted as sec\nretary in the absence of Mrs. Mag\ngie Viar, and read the minutes of\nthe previous meeting and the reg\nular routine of business was trans\ni acted.\nI The Statewide Labor Day cele\nbration was discussed and all seem\nFRENCH WORKERS\nSTRIKE FOR\nINCREASED WAGES\nParis, France. A wide-spread\nstrike affecting the industrial re\ngion of northern France has been\ndeclared. Th/\u00bb organized metal,\nbuilding and textile workers are\nleading the movement.\nThe workers demand increased\nwages to reimburse them for the\nincreased cost of living caused by\nthe new social insurance law, un\nder which they are compelled to\npay definite percentages of their\nwages to the insurance fund. Or\nganized employers generally have\nrefused to grant the increase.\nIn some instances employers\nhave offered to pay the workers\u2019\nsocial insurance dues as a bonus\nat the end of th/j yoar to all work\ners who have been regular in at\ntendance and against whom there\nhave been no complaints. Organ\nized labor has rejected this \u201cgood\nconduct\u201d recompense and insists\nthat wages must be increased to\nmake up for the social insurance\nI\nMOONEY-BILLINGS WORK\nDESCRIBED BY NOCKELS\nI .San Francisco, Calif. Edward\nN. Nockels, secretary of th/; Chi\nago Federation of Labor, told the\nCalifornia '.Supreme Court of his\n1 years\u2019 work in behalf of Mooney\nand Billings now serving life sen\ntences for th/*ir alleged participa\ntion in the bomb explosions on\nPreparedness Day in 191G. Nockels\nexplained how he located John\nMacDonald, confessed perjurer in\nthe trials of the two men, and did\nother work in their behalf.\nHe said he knew of no money re\nj reived by MacDonald except the ex\npenses of his trip to th* coast in\n1921, which Nockels paid on behalf\nof the Chicago Federation.\nNEW INDUSTRIAL\nDISEASE HANDED\nOUT TO WORKERS\nLondon.\u2014The increasing use of\nasbestos in industry has subjected\nthe workers to a new occupational\ndisease affecting the lungs, accord\ning to Sir Thomas Oliver, well\nknown expert on Industrial dis\neases. \u201cPulmonary asbestosis,\u201d the\nscientific name for the new disease,\nI disables and ultimately kills the\noil anxious to have a float in the\nparade, as well aa to help in other\nways. \u00abj\nMrs. Dora Strickland, C. E.\nChastain, Lena Ashley and Nellie\nWebster were appointed to attend\ntho meeting of the Statewide Labor\nDay Committee Wednesday night,\nAugust 13 and learn in what ways\nthe Ladies Society to the Brother\nhood of Locomotive Firemen and\nEnginemen could further assist\nthem in this elaborate celebration.\nTho meeting adjourned at 3:30\np. m. and as the vacation season is\nabout over and business is\npicking up generally, it is expected\nto have better meeting in the fu\nture, and all members arc therefore\nurged to attend regularly.\n\u2018LOST DOCUMENTS\nSUPPORT M\u2019DONALD\nSan Francisco. Call\u00a3\ndocuments \u201clost\u201d for 14 years, Wes*\npresented to the California Su\npreme Court in the examination of\nJohn MacDonald, retracting wit\nness in the Preparedness Day\nbombing trials, to refute his origi\nn'll identification of Thomas\n-Mooney and Warren K. Billings,\nnow serving life terms for the\nbombing.\nThe documents were a report\nmade by MacDonald to the police\ntwo days after the bombing, July\n22, 1916, in which his descriptions\nof the two men he claimed were\nimplicated in the bombing varied\ndefinitely from being true descrip\ntions of Mooney and Billings. In\nspite of police knowledge of these\nreports, MacDonald was put on to\nidentify Mooney and Billings as\ntho men he saw place the bomb.\nA. F. L ORGANIZATION\nEXTENDING IN SOUTH\nBirmingham, Ala.\u2014The decision\nof the southern organization com\nmittee of the American Federation\nof Labor to open up a new field\nof organization work in the textile\nindustry has given new impetus to\nthe work in the South.\nFrancis J. Gorman, international\nvice president of the United Textile\nworkers, has just completed a tour\nof the textile fields and found or\nganizating work active. He told the\ncohimitteo he was well Satisfied\nwith tho progress being made, and\nrecommended that additional terri\ntory be included hi the union activ\nities.\nThe territory includes a region\nthrough western Alabama and on\ndown through to Co\u2019....:bus, Ga. A\nUnited Textile organizer will work\nout of Anniston, Ala., where head\nquarters will be maintained. Local\nunions at Columbus, Danville, Va.,\nAnniston, Huntsville and elsewhere\nwere reported to be gaining in\nmembership.\nPUBLIC OWNEDSHII* TO BE\nISSUE\nr\nNew York.\u2014The state committee\nof the Socialist Party will make\nthe public ownership of electric\nlight and power facilities the ma\njor issue in the New York state\nelection this fall.\nThe committee ta'ade provision\nfor the inclusion of non-party\nmembers on special committees for\njthe mobilization of independeal","height":"21220","width":"17412"}}
